    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense. so if the ph is off is it basically like the nutrients are just stuck there and the plant cant reach them? feels like something is actively preventing it from eating properly. how can i tell if the ph is the reason they aren't getting what they need?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You've hit on the nail on the head; it's like the nutrients are locked away in a cage, and the plant's roots can't get the key to unlock them. If the pH is off, it creates an environment where certain minerals become chemically unavailable, even if you've dumped a whole pile of fertilizer on the soil. A soil test is the definitive way to know, but if you don't have one, you can try adding a soil pH test kit, which is relatively inexpensive. If the kit shows your pH is way out of the sweet spot, you can adjust it using lime (to raise pH) or sulfur (to lower pH).",
      "source": "target",
